-- Hong Kong shares close higher as China stocks sizzle
-- By the Shanghai Newsroom
-- Thu Dec 04, 2014 03:10AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 4 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares rose on Thursday as mainland China markets extended their blistering rally, with financial and energy stocks leading the gains.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> rose 1.7 percen, to 23,832.56 points, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> gained 3.8 percent, to 11,481.03 points.  China stocks soared to their highest level since mid-2011 on Thursday, led by financial and oil shares, as the market's rally on expectations of further economic stimulus measures showed no signs of losing steam. [.SS]   Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were CCT Land Holding <0261.HK>, down 6.3 percent to HK$0.02, Bank Of China <3988.HK>, up 3.2 percent to HK$4.16 and China Construction Bank <0939.HK>, up 2.4 percent to HK$5.99. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 0.41 billion yuan of the 10.5 billion yuan ($1.7 billion) daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>.